00:12:02.540 --> 00:12:04.450
&gt;&gt; Josiah Blackmore: Yes, yes.

00:12:04.450 --> 00:12:09.590
So one of the questions Francisco
asked us to think about is,

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:15.040
"Why "Queer Iberia"," in
addition to what we've just said.

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:19.780
And the subtitle -- to us one
of the most important words

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:25.010
of the subtitle is "crossings,"
because in Iberia, of course,

00:12:25.010 --> 00:12:31.850
there are borders and frontiers
of many kinds; cultures,

00:12:31.850 --> 00:12:35.450
sexuality, language, religion.

00:12:35.450 --> 00:12:42.630
And these borders suggest
something very rich and faceted

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:47.240
that we wanted to explore
as a whole.

00:12:47.240 --> 00:12:52.470
So between the kingdoms of
what is now modern-day Spain,

00:12:52.470 --> 00:12:54.090
and the kingdom of Portugal,

00:12:54.090 --> 00:12:59.850
which came to have its current
political boundaries in 1248,

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:05.670
we were looking to think about how
there was a certain fungability

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:11.210
[phonetic], or precocity, as
opposed to walls and obstacles.

00:13:11.210 --> 00:13:19.250
So it very much was a project of
border crossings of many kinds.

00:13:19.250 --> 00:13:22.670
And I think when we were
putting together the volume

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:27.180
and doing our own essays,
we certainly felt that.

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:32.880 position:56%
And in the past 17 years, that's one
of the things I think that people

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:36.410
at least have said to me most of
all is how much they appreciate

00:13:36.410 --> 00:13:42.760
that Iberian perspective
as a historical reality,

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:46.190
as a methodology, as a
critical methodology.

00:13:46.190 --> 00:13:50.050
So it was something we became very
invested in, wouldn't you say?

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:51.350
&gt;&gt; Gregory Hutcheson: Absolutely.

00:13:51.350 --> 00:13:56.490
I would also say that our queering
of medieval Iberia really --

00:13:56.490 --> 00:14:00.720
we ended up contextualizing it
through a different kind of query,

00:14:00.720 --> 00:14:04.810
a cultural query that had
already been a bit realized

00:14:04.810 --> 00:14:06.340
by Americo Castro.

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:10.150
Americo Castro is one of the
great Hispanics [phonetic]

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:11.910
of the middle 20th century.

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:15.240
He proposed a radically
different reading of the medieval

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:18.190
and early modern context in
Iberia, one which took him

00:14:18.190 --> 00:14:22.680
to far greater consideration
the 800th year presence

00:14:22.680 --> 00:14:24.560
of Islam in Iberia.

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:25.890
And you can see on the map that's

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:31.650
on the screen right now the
furthest most northern region --

00:14:31.650 --> 00:14:37.190
or border between Christian
Europe and what was

00:14:37.190 --> 00:14:40.220
at that time Muslim Europe.

00:14:40.220 --> 00:14:44.950
The Muslim presence in Iberia
began in 711 with a crossing

00:14:44.950 --> 00:14:50.460
of Arabic peoples along with Berber
peoples into the space of Iberia,

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:53.390
moved to the -- virtually
to the border with France,

00:14:53.390 --> 00:14:55.660
and progressively over the course

00:14:55.660 --> 00:15:00.570
of several centuries the Christian
north began pushing southward.

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:03.160
But that border -- as Joe implied,

00:15:03.160 --> 00:15:07.340
that border was always a porous
border, one not simply of conflict,

00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:09.580
but also of cultural negotiation.

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:13.420
Medieval -- if you switch to the
next side that will give us a sense

00:15:13.420 --> 00:15:17.950
of medieval Castro's
notion of medieval Iberia.

00:15:17.950 --> 00:15:20.340
This probably summarizes it best.

00:15:20.340 --> 00:15:22.490
It's from his Espania
in Historia Spain

00:15:22.490 --> 00:15:25.080
and its history that
came out in 1948.

00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:27.780
He says that the most
universal aspect

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:30.130
of Hispanic character
traced their roots

00:15:30.130 --> 00:15:33.180
to lifestyles forged
during 900 years

00:15:33.180 --> 00:15:35.720
of Christian Islamic
Jewish intermingling.

00:15:35.720 --> 00:15:41.550
This brought rise -- this, as we
call it, the "cultural queering

00:15:41.550 --> 00:15:46.980
of Iberia," the destabilizing
of Iberia as centered in Europe,

00:15:46.980 --> 00:15:50.730
this brought rise to
immediate response in the part

00:15:50.730 --> 00:15:52.950
of more nationalist
leading scholars,

00:15:52.950 --> 00:15:58.710
such as Claudio Sanchez-Albornoz,
who re-described Iberia

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:03.370
in the context of Europe and
moreover, portrayed Iberian Spain

00:16:03.370 --> 00:16:07.300
in particular as the
shield of Christian Europe

00:16:07.300 --> 00:16:10.910
against the Islamic intrusion.

00:16:10.910 --> 00:16:15.140
And eventually, that
re-conquest that what was termed,

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:17.440
the "Christian re-conquest
of Spain,"

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:22.390
it eventually had its culmination
in 1492, red-letter year,

00:16:22.390 --> 00:16:25.440
we just celebrated it
I guess the other day,

